properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Temperatures reaching 32 degrees Celsius combined with overnight lows near 16 degrees Celsius are expected for the next 2 days. A hot air mass will spread across southern Saskatchewan this week, sending temperatures into the low 30s with overnight lows in the mid-teens. The heat will be concentrated over the southwest corner of the province today, but will spread eastwards with increasing humidity through the week. In the southwest, slightly cooler temperatures will bring an end to the warning level conditions for Friday. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. Watch for the effects of heat illness: swelling, rash, cramps, fainting, heat exhaustion, heat stroke and the worsening of some health conditions. Please call HealthLine 811 for advice on health risks, symptoms and precautions associated with heat. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Humidex values reaching 33 are expected for the next 3 days. Heat event expected to start Thursday Temperatures are expected to reach near 30 degrees Thursday until Saturday. Hot and humid air can also bring deteriorating air quality and can result in the Air Quality Health Index to approach the high risk category. Somewhat cooler and less humid air will arrive on Sunday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Hot and humid conditions are expected to break over inland portions of southern and western Nova Scotia this evening. Time span: early this evening. Maximum daytime temperatures: near 29 degrees Celsius, except cooler along parts of the coast. Locations: southern and western Nova Scotia. Remarks: Temperatures have peaked to near 29 degree today for most of the inland area of southern and western Nova Scotia. While humidex values will reach the low 30s over much of the province tomorrow, maximum temperatures are expected to reach only the mid 20s and this warning will be ended this evening as temperatures begin to cool. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. Heat warnings are issued when very high temperature or humidity conditions are expected to pose an elevated risk of heat illnesses, such as heat stroke or heat exhaustion. Information is provided on the Nova Scotia Department of Health and Wellness website at https://novascotia.ca/heat-related-illness/. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.
